SIMPLE: treble
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treble
<hw>Tre"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>treble</ets>
threefold, OF. <ets>treble</ets>, <ets>treible</ets>, L.
<ets>triplus</ets>. See <er>Triple</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Threefold; triple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lofty tower, and strong on every side⟦br⟧
With <qex>treble</qex> walls.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Acute; sharp; <as>as,
a <ex>treble</ex> sound</as>.</def> <au>Bacon.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Playing or singing the highest part or most acute sounds; playing
or singing the treble; <as>as, a <ex>treble</ex> violin or
voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Treble
<hw>Tre"ble</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Trebly; triply.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>J. Fletcher.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Treble
<hw>Tre"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[⟦ldquo⟧ It has been said to be a
corruption of <ets>triplum</ets> [Lat.], a third part, superadded to the
altus and bassus (high and low).⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Grove.</au>]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The highest of the four principal parts in music;
the part usually sung by boys or women; soprano.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This is sometimes called the <xex>first treble</xex>, to
distinguish it from the <xex>second treble</xex>, or <xex>alto</xex>,
which is sung by lower female voices.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Treble
<hw>Tre"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trebled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trebling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make thrice as
much; to make threefold.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Love <xex>trebled</xex>
life.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter in a treble key; to whine.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He outrageously⟦br⟧
(When I accused him) <qex>trebled</qex> his reply.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Treble
<hw>Tre"ble</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become threefold.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trebleness</ent>⟦br⟧
